# Fluff Date: 2026-02-26 19:50:04
<overview>
<p>The Quixote-class frigate holds the dubious distinction of being one of the Terran Hegemony Navy's most notorious procurement failures, yet it went on to serve capably for nearly two centuries as a dedicated missile platform. Originally designated as a battlecruiser, the design was reclassified midway through development when engineers reused drives from the smaller Lola-class destroyer, producing a vessel far too slow for its intended role. A procurement bureaucrat then authorized two hundred fifty hulls for production, an act later suspected of being deliberate sabotage to circumvent Admiralty spending objections. Redesignated as a missile frigate and armed accordingly, the Quixote found its niche escorting convoys before the Congress-class frigate rendered it obsolete. Mothballed Quixote hulls later found new purpose when converted into the Volga-class transport, and at least one vessel survived into the thirty-first century as the TCS Vendetta, refurbished by the Word of Blake for the Taurian Concordat.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>Displacing 780,000 tons across 715 meters of hull, the Quixote carries the heaviest missile armament of any Star League-era frigate. Eighteen Killer Whale launchers form the backbone of the weapons suite, with six mounted in the nose and paired launchers covering every other arc. Twenty-four White Shark and twenty-four Barracuda capital missile launchers supplement the Killer Whales, creating overlapping fields of missile fire that made the Quixote lethal to anything within range. Two NAC/30 naval autocannons and six NL55 naval lasers provide additional firepower at closer ranges. One thousand one hundred seventy-seven single heat sinks manage the thermal output, while nearly 1,200 tons of improved ferro-aluminum armor give the frigate protection exceeding most heavy cruisers. Six docking collars support a substantial transport capacity, complemented by twelve fighter bays, six small craft bays, and over 176,000 tons of cargo space. Three gravity decks -- one at 120 meters and two at 145 meters -- serve a crew of over 480 personnel including 150 marines. Safe thrust of two and maximum thrust of three reflect the undersized drives inherited from the Lola-class destroyer, the critical weakness that ultimately doomed the design to early replacement by the faster Congress-class.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The most remarkable individual Quixote is the vessel known successively as TCS Vendetta, CPS Redemption, and RSS Redemption. Originally a mothballed Star League-era hull, the Word of Blake refurbished the vessel and gifted it to the Taurian Concordat in 3074. As TCS Vendetta, it became the centerpiece of Taurian retaliatory strikes during the Jihad, conducting orbital bombardments across multiple Federated Suns worlds including Warren, Keuterville, and New Syrtis. At Brusett in 3075, the Vendetta engaged and destroyed the FCS Kathil before being forced to retreat. After hitting a minefield at Firgrove in 3080, the damaged vessel was transferred to the Calderon Protectorate by treaty in 3081 and renamed CPS Redemption, serving as the only active warship in the Periphery. Decades later, as RSS Redemption under the Republic of the Sphere, the ancient frigate participated in Task Force Walkure during the ilClan crisis, firing every available battery at the Jade Falcon Blue Talon before ramming it in a final act of defiance.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Quixote-class frigate entered service with the Terran Hegemony Navy in 2350 under circumstances that would become legendary for all the wrong reasons. The vessel was originally conceived as a battlecruiser, but the SLDF reclassified it as a frigate during the design process. Engineers attempting to reduce costs reused the drive systems from the Lola-class destroyer, a critical miscalculation that left the massive 780,000-ton vessel woefully underpowered with a maximum thrust of only three. Compounding the design failure, a bureaucrat in the Procurement Department authorized two hundred fifty hulls for production -- later evidence suggesting this was a deliberate act to circumvent Admiralty objections and curb naval spending at a time when resources were slim. The Admiralty, stuck with a mediocre ship, adapted by reclassifying it as a missile frigate and loading it with the heaviest missile armament available. Eighteen Killer Whale launchers, supplemented by dozens of White Shark and Barracuda tubes, made the Quixote genuinely dangerous despite its sluggish performance. Nearly 1,200 tons of improved ferro-aluminum armor gave it better protection than most heavy cruisers, and convoy escorts like the Farragut and Monsoon welcomed the missile coverage the class provided. By 2536, Hegemony admirals concluded the Quixote had outlived its usefulness, as incidents demonstrated it could be outmaneuvered by virtually any foreign-built vessel of comparable size. A year later, Dekirk Aerospace submitted the Congress-class frigate design as a replacement, and the Quixotes were gradually retired to mothball yards. Beginning in 2709, the mothballed hulls were reactivated and converted into the Volga-class transport, with the Quixote's undersized drives proving ideally suited for a slower cargo vessel. At least one Quixote accompanied General Kerensky's Exodus fleet, and during Operation Klondike a spacefarer-operated Quixote at Circe's zenith point escaped Clan forces amid a desperate running battle. While the accompanying Potemkin was captured two weeks later, the Quixote was never seen again. The class returned to prominence during the Jihad when the Word of Blake refurbished a mothballed hull and gifted it to the Taurian Concordat as TCS Vendetta in 3074, making it the centerpiece of Taurian retaliatory strikes against the Federated Suns. The vessel passed through three nations' service -- Taurian Concordat, Calderon Protectorate, and Republic of the Sphere -- before meeting its end ramming a Clan Jade Falcon warship during the ilClan crisis, a fitting conclusion for a design that had always exceeded expectations despite its troubled origins.</p>
</history>

